posts.summary: Perfect by Gianni Cipriano The greatest perfection is imperfection. To Aristotle perfect meant complete, nothing to add or...
posts.caption:
Perfect by Gianni Cipriano

The greatest perfection is imperfection.

To Aristotle perfect meant complete, nothing to add or subtract. To Empedocles perfection depends on incompleteness since the latter possesses a potential for development and improvement. Here lies the paradox formulated by Italian Renaissance philosopher Giulio Cesare Vanini. The paradox of perfection is that imperfection is perfect.

I travelled around Italy researching imperfect beauties in six different non-conventional beauty pageants and applied a color symbolism to each one:

Miss Chubby, pink;
Miss Trans, purple;
Miss Mediterranea, yellow;
Miss Plastic Surgery, fuchsia;
Miss Drag Queen, orange;
Miss Over, blue.

Six imperfect beauties (due to their weight, clothes, excess of silicone, or age) if compared to the typology of beauty imposed by mass media and the consumerist society we live in. In Italy, in particular, beauty has become a political tool during the Berlusconi era. Since the 80’s, his media empire has introduced a culture of luxury and sex to shape his electorate. Italy became in the mean time a country where half-naked beautiful women are plucked from TV studios and elevated into powerful positions. This culture has generated an unprecedented wave of castings and beauty pageants for girls and women of all ages all over Italy.

In response to the aesthetic and political state of my country, I worked on Perfect, a series of 36 photographs focusing on how the beauty dictated by our politicized consumerist society is emulated by the masses, and on the link between imperfection and perfection. (by Gianni Cipriano)

posts.summary:
Paintings by Anne-Marie Kornachuk
 I am interested in looking at states of being; spaces and events that create many questions...
posts.caption:
turecepcja:

Paintings by Anne-Marie Kornachuk

I am interested in looking at states of being; spaces and events that create many questions and answers and can be looked at in positive and negative ways. I use figurative gesture, color, and composition to speak about these internal states. I intentionally convey only small details of the body. These figurative details speak for the body as a whole. They also represent moments of intense intimacy, placing the viewer in the position of voyeur or participant. The animated nature of the fabric, which overwhelms the figure at times, plays multiple roles. I see a kind of operatic drama in the beauty, complexity and rippling energy of the fabric as if the fabric is alive with the hidden internal dramas of the figure (…)

posts.summary: Appalachian Summer, 2018, Volume Forty: Broadleaf Arrowhead. For muskrats, beavers, snapping turtles, and over a dozen species...
posts.caption:
vandaliatraveler:

Appalachian Summer, 2018, Volume Forty: Broadleaf Arrowhead. For muskrats, beavers, snapping turtles, and over a dozen species of ducks, broadleaf arrowhead (Sagittaria latifolia) is a veritable cornucopia of edible delights, from the starchy tubers that form from its branching rhizomes to the seeds that follow its flowers in the fall. One of the plant’s common names is duck-potato. Arrowhead’s starchy tuber was also an important food source for Native Americans; the Cree knew the plant as the wapato. Native plant gatherers still occasionally harvest arrowhead for food. A recipe for making arrowhead chips can be found here. A member of the water-plantain family (Alismataceae), this aquatic perennial herb forms dense colonies in the still water at the margins of large rivers and streams and in marshes and water-logged soils throughout Appalachia. The plant’s highly characteristic, arrow-shaped leaves rise on long stems as much as three feet above the water level or mud substrate. In late summer and early fall, small white flowers studded with numerous yellow stamens form in whorls of three around a long, leafless stalk. In addition to being an important food source for wildlife, broadleaf arrowhead provides valuable wildlife cover for aquatic fowl and is readily propagated as an ornamental plant in water gardens and ponds.

 Unknown English artist
 Portrait of a Labrador Woman (Caubvick of Labrador)
 England (c.1772)
 Oil on...
posts.caption:
medievalpoc:

aseantoo submitted:

Unknown English artist

Portrait of a Labrador Woman (Caubvick of Labrador)

England (c.1772)

Oil on canvas, 75 x 63 cm

The Royal College of Surgeons of England

[Source]

Wikipedia says:

Caubvick (fl. 1773) was an Inuk from Labrador, a wife of one of George Cartwright’s Inuit friends. The highest peak in all of Labrador and east of the Rockies is named in her honour, Mount Caubvick.

In 1773, George Cartwright took Attuiock and Tooklavina and their wives, including Caubvick, to England where they met with the king, members of the Royal Society and James Boswell[1] The Inuit all developed smallpox while in England. Caubvick was the only survivor of the group. She returned to her native Labrador and passed on the dreaded disease to many of her people.

posts.summary: MOSCOW — A sculpture by Pawel Althamer, a small knight by Marino Marini, a terracotta head by the Nok people from Nigeria: all...
posts.caption:
hyperallergic:

MOSCOW — A sculpture by Pawel Althamer, a small knight by Marino Marini, a terracotta head by the Nok people from Nigeria: all are grouped together on a rough wooden platform, with no apparent logic, in Mike Nelson’s “Again, More Things (a table ruin)” (2014). First shown at the Whitechapel Gallery in London, Nelson’s piece greets the visitors of the exhibition General Rehearsal, closing soon at the Moscow Museum of Modern Art’s (MMOMA) historic Petrovka Street Gallery.

(via Reimagining Artworks as Actors and the Gallery as a Stage)

posts.summary: “Default” is a photo zine by Ryuta Abe (previously featured here). Published by Koshigoe School, the 36 page black and white...
posts.caption:
nopefun:

“Default” is a photo zine by Ryuta Abe (previously featured here). Published by Koshigoe School, the 36 page black and white publication is a search for silence in his environment.

The zine presents a shift in his photographic practise: taking pictures from an angle which highlights the spatial qualities of his surroundings. Roads, fences, bridges and stairs are composed to create long diagonal lines, leading the eye to a vanishing point outside of frame.

He writes, “For me everything around me were an irritative agents…[despite] living in a laid-back port town. So I was walking around and looking for the moment which I could breath and record them.” It is in these man-made structures that are devoid of people where he is able to find, or perhaps create through the camera, his own space.

Get a copy here. Check out more publication reviews at our bookshelf.

Get more updates on our Facebook page and Instagram.
